@mahmoud  @markrwilliams Okay - so I thought about it a lot more. I've fixed the implementation so that it will pass @markrwilliams devious and horrifying (to me) tests. I've included an implementation of his test in the test suite, just for defensive purposes.

I nearly went ahead and with the utf-32 route - but I got partway, realized that the byte markers created an annoying offset that was making the implementation kind of annoying; at least to me it was about as annoying as utf-8. I suspect that the main use cases for SpooledStringIO are to be replacing StringIO, and StringIO with unicode characters tends to come into play when people need a file like object interface for something, but can't control whether or not they get random unicode characters. Dropping this in can have memory savings; with utf-32 I'd bet that most of the time smaller sets of data would be inflated by 4x as most of the characters are likely to be ascii. That made the nice variable byte width of utf-8 so enticing that I just couldn't resist the savings. 

The implementation of seek and len are probably the only parts at this point that takes any measurable performance hit from implementing seek on top of reads. Most of the time though I don't think that people will be doing lots of arbitrary seeking (except maybe back to zero).

