This isn't discussed in the documentation, as it is a general flask issue, but running the app via `app.run(debug=True)` should only be used for local/development. It uses flask's built in server and is not secure and can only handle one request at a time. 

Check out flask's [deployment documentation](http://flask.pocoo.org/docs/0.12/deploying/). The options described there should also help get an idea of how to get a public URL for your webhook (heroku is very easy to set up).

this is a bug in all types of requests that go though botocore, here's a quick workaround for you:
i'll make a pull request shortly

```
def _release_botocore_http_connection(http_response=None, **kwargs):
    if http_response is not None and http_response.raw and http_response.status_code < 300:
        # this corresponds to code in botocore/client.py _make_api_call where status_code >= 300 is error handled
        http_response.raw.release_conn()

def fix_botocore_http_release(client):
    if hasattr(client.meta, 'client'):
        target = client.meta.client
    else:
        target = client
    target.meta.events.register('after-call', _release_botocore_http_connection)
    return client
```

